### RULE 5: Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF) — CWE-918

**BAD — User-controlled URLs fetched server-side:**
```
FUNCTION fetch_url(request):
    url = request.params.url
    response = http.get(url)                   // Attacker controls target
    RETURN response
// Attack: url = "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"  (AWS metadata)
// Attack: url = "http://localhost:6379/"  (internal Redis)
// Attack: url = "file:///etc/passwd"
```

**GOOD — Allowlist and validate:**
```
FUNCTION fetch_url(request):
    url = request.params.url
    parsed = parse_url(url)

    // Scheme allowlist
    IF parsed.scheme NOT IN ["http", "https"]: REJECT

    // Resolve DNS BEFORE fetching (prevent DNS rebinding)
    ip = dns.resolve(parsed.hostname)

    // Block internal/private ranges
    IF is_private_ip(ip) OR is_loopback(ip) OR is_link_local(ip): REJECT

    // Allowlist destination domains if possible
    IF parsed.hostname NOT IN ALLOWED_DOMAINS: REJECT

    response = http.get(url, follow_redirects=false)  // Don't follow redirects to internal
    RETURN response
```

**Also check for:**
- DNS rebinding: validate IP AFTER resolution, not just hostname
- Redirect following: server follows redirect from allowed domain to internal IP
- URL parsing inconsistencies: different parsers handling `http://evil.com@internal/` differently
- Cloud metadata endpoints: `169.254.169.254` (AWS), `metadata.google.internal` (GCP)
- Webhooks, image fetchers, PDF generators, link previews — all common SSRF vectors

